, Regean, Yves.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by a gateway or barrier, or in a house encircled by a fence, from Old French <i>barre</i> ‘bar, obstruction’ (of obscure origin, possibly akin to the Celtic element <i>barr</i> ‘height’); or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, e.g. Barre-en-Ouche in Eure or Barre-de-Semilly in Manche. Compare   Labarre  .","French: probably also a habitational name from Barre in Lozère, named with the Celtic element <i>barr</i> ‘height’."],"variants":[{"name":"Labarre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Alain, Andre, Armand, Aurore, Fernande, Gilles, Herve, Laure, Michel, Urbain.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by a gateway or barrier, or in a house encircled by a fence, from Old French <i>barre</i> ‘bar, obstruction’ (see   Barre   1), with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, e.g. Barre-en-Ouche in Eure or Barre-de-Semilly in Manche. Compare   Labar  ,   Labare  ,   Labarr  ,   Labor  ,   Labore  ,   Lebar  , and   Lebarre  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Jacques Genest or Genet <i>dit</i> Labarre from France (see   Genest  )."]},{"name":"Baray","meanings":["Hispanic (Mexico): unexplained.","In some cases possibly also French: variant of <b>Barray</b>, itself a variant of <b>Barrey</b>, a derivative of   Barre   1. In France, it is found mainly in Seine-Maritime."]},{"name":"Barrere","meanings":["French (<b>Barrère</b>): topographic name for someone who lived by a gate or barrier, or a metonymic occupational name for a gatekeeper, from a derivative of Old French <i>bar(r)e</i> ‘bar, rod’, in the sense of ‘barrier’ (compare   Barre   1); or a habitational name from (La) Barrère, the name of several places in the southwestern part of France.","English: variant of <b>Barrer</b>, for someone who lived by a town or castle gate, from Middle English <i>barre</i> ‘barrier, gateway’. Compare above and   Barr   4."]},{"name":"Barriere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Gaston, Monique, Philippe.","French (<b>Barrière</b>): topographic name for someone who lived by a gate or barrier, or a metonymic occupational name for a gatekeeper, from a derivative of Old French <i>bar(r)e</i> ‘bar, rod’, in the sense of ‘barrier’ (compare   Barre   1); or a habitational name from (La) Barrière, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Gates  ."]},{"name":"Barreau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Fresnel, Gabrielle, Jean-Louis, Jean-Marie, Jeanty, Michel, Michelene, Pierre.","French:","derivative of Old French <i>bar(r)e</i> ‘bar, rod’, in the sense of ‘barrier’ (compare   Barre   1), hence a nickname for a fence keeper or a topographic name for someone who lived in a house encircled by a fence."]},{"name":"Barrier","meanings":["French: occupational name for a gatekeeper, from Old French <i>barier</i>, an agent derivative of <i>bar(r)e</i> ‘bar, rod’, in the sense of ‘barrier’ (compare   Barre   1).","Altered form of French   Barriere  .","Altered form of German   Berger  ."]},{"name":"Barra","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Marina, Antonio, Augusto, Biagio, Carlo, Domenic, Flavio, Gennaro, Lorenzo, Luciano, Rocco, Salvatore.  Spanish Jorge, Carlos, Diego, Enrique, Jaime, Juan, Manuel.","Italian (southern), Spanish, and Portuguese: topographic name from <i>barra</i> ‘bar, rod’ (in the sense of ‘barrier, sandbank’), or a habitational name from any of the places called with this word.","French (southern): dialect variant of   Barre   1."]}]},{"name":"Joanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Joannah","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."]},{"name":"Joana","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joanna Barre was born in 1373, in Wales, her father, Sir Thomas de la Barre, was 25 and her mother, Elizabeth Croyser, was 23. She had at least 1 daughter with John de la Bere IV. She died in 1421, in her hometown, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1373–1421":"1373–1421","1368–1419":"1368–1419","1389–Female":"1389–Surnud","–1468":"–1468","1385–1445":"1385–1445","1368–1402":"1368–1402","1402–1450":"1402–1450","1349–1419":"1349–1419","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1385":"1385","1373":"1373","1450":"1450","1350":"1350","18 December 1419":"18. detsember 1419","15 December 1420":"15. detsember 1420","1349":"1349","abt 1402":"umbes 1402","1402":"1402","1468":"1468","1445":"1445","1368":"1368","1389":"1389","1421":"1421","1420":"1420","before 1381":"enne 1381","1419":"1419","22 June 1402":"22. juuni 1402","Wales":"Wales","England":"England","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Clehonger, Herefordshire, England":"Clehonger, Herefordshire, England","Gwyr, Glamorgan, Wales":"Gwyr, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"1373–1421":"1373–1421","1368–1419":"1368–1419","1389–Female":"1389–Kuollut","–1468":"–1468","1385–1445":"1385–1445","1368–1402":"1368–1402","1402–1450":"1402–1450","1349–1419":"1349–1419","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1385":"1385","1373":"1373","1450":"1450","1350":"1350","18 December 1419":"18. joulukuuta 1419","15 December 1420":"15. joulukuuta 1420","1349":"1349","abt 1402":"noin 1402","1402":"1402","1468":"1468","1445":"1445","1368":"1368","1389":"1389","1421":"1421","1420":"1420","before 1381":"ennen vuotta 1381","1419":"1419","22 June 1402":"22. kesäkuuta 1402","Wales":"Wales","England":"England","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Clehonger, Herefordshire, England":"Clehonger, Herefordshire, England","Gwyr, Glamorgan, Wales":"Gwyr, Glamorgan, 